There are multiple points that you need to take care of.

If you need to run your program multiple times then you need to a sentinel controlled loop (e.g. controlled by a condition such as yes/no or specific number of repetitions), not an infinite loop i.e. `while(1)`. If not, the `while` loop is unnecessary.

At the end of the program, `getchar()` blocks until &lt;kbd&gt;ENTER&lt;/kbd&gt; is pressed so you don&#39;t need that `while(1)` there.

You can simply use a block for writing multiple statements in your `if-else-if` so you don&#39;t have to check for the index again at the end e.g.:

    if ((x1 &gt; x2) &amp;&amp; (x1 &gt; x3) &amp;&amp; (x1 &gt; x4))
    { 
    	xlarge = x1; // assign the number to xlarge, not x1 = xlarge
    	ixlarge = 1; // assign the position of the number here!!!
    }

You&#39;re assigning `x1 = xlarge;` which is incorrect as `x1` already contains a value input by the user. This value will be overwritten by a garbage value stored in `xlarge` because it has not been initialized. It should be: `xlarge = x1;`.

In an `if-else`, you don&#39;t need to check the last condition i.e. three alternatives have been tested so you can simply write the last result without testing it in the `else`.

         if ( condition-1 ) /* do something */
    else if ( condition-2 ) /* do something */
    else if ( condition-3 ) /* do something */
    else                    /* do something if all other conditions are false */

Always initialize your variables so that you know for sure that they are in a known state and won&#39;t cause a *used-before-initialization* causing [Undefined Behavior][1].

Here&#39;s an example ([live][2]):

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    
    int main(void)
    {
        int x1 = 0, x2 = 0, x3 = 0, x4 = 0;
        int xlarge = 0, xsmall = 0, ixlarge = 0, ixsmall = 0;
    
        printf(&quot;Enter x1, x2, x3, x4: &quot;);
        scanf(&quot;%d %d %d %d&quot;, &amp;x1, &amp;x2, &amp;x3, &amp;x4);
    
        if ((x1 &gt; x2) &amp;&amp; (x1 &gt; x3) &amp;&amp; (x1 &gt; x4))
        { 
        	xlarge = x1;
        	ixlarge = 1;
        }
        else if ((x2 &gt; x1) &amp;&amp; (x2 &gt; x3) &amp;&amp; (x2 &gt; x4))
        { 
        	xlarge = x2;
        	ixlarge = 2;
        }
        else if ((x3 &gt; x1) &amp;&amp; (x3 &gt; x2) &amp;&amp; (x3 &gt; x4))
        { 
        	xlarge = x3;
        	ixlarge = 3;
        }
        else if ((x4 &gt; x1) &amp;&amp; (x4 &gt; x2) &amp;&amp; (x4 &gt; x3))
        { 
        	xlarge = x4;
        	ixlarge = 4;
        }
    
        if ((x1 &lt; x2) &amp;&amp; (x1 &lt; x3) &amp;&amp; (x1 &lt; x4))
        {
           	xsmall = x1;
           	ixsmall = 1;
        }
        else if ((x2 &lt; x1) &amp;&amp; (x2 &lt; x3) &amp;&amp; (x2 &lt; x4))
        {
           	xsmall = x2;
           	ixsmall = 2;
        }
        else if ((x3 &lt; x1) &amp;&amp; (x3 &lt; x2) &amp;&amp; (x3 &lt; x4))
        {
           	xsmall = x3;
           	ixsmall = 3;
        }
        else if ((x4 &lt; x1) &amp;&amp; (x4 &lt; x2) &amp;&amp; (x4 &lt; x3))
        {
           	xsmall = x4;
           	ixsmall = 4;
        }
    
        printf(&quot;Largest  %d @ [index: %d]\n&quot;, xlarge, ixlarge);
        printf(&quot;Smallest %d @ [index: %d]\n&quot;, xsmall, ixsmall);
     
        return 0;
    }

Output:

    Enter x1, x2, x3, x4: 1 2 3 4
    Largest  4 @ [index: 4]
    Smallest 1 @ [index: 1]

---

If you&#39;re allowed to use macros then you can write for your conditions:

    #define IS_GREATER(n,x,y,z)		((n &gt; x) &amp;&amp; (n &gt; y) &amp;&amp; (n &gt; z))
    #define IS_SMALLER(n,x,y,z)		((n &lt; x) &amp;&amp; (n &lt; y) &amp;&amp; (n &lt; z))

