Resolving an identifier (in order of descending priority):

1. Syntactically-defined meaning, when syntactically expected.

        sub foo { }     # &#171;foo&#187; (&#171;sub&#187; is covered later)
        $foo
        //i
        =head

1. String literal, when followed by a `=&gt;` or when the entirety of a hash index expression.

        my %h = ( a =&gt; 1 );
        $h{a}

1. Keyword.

        while (1) { }
        sub { }
        BEGIN { }

1. Sub call, when the name of a previously imported sub.

        use Time::HiRes qw( time );
        time

1. Invocation of a named list operator, named unary operator or named nullary operator.

        print $x, $y, $z;
        $c = chr $i;
        $t = time;

1. Sub call, when the name of a previously declared sub.

        sub foo { }
        foo

        sub bar;
        bar

        use constant FOO =&gt; 123;
        FOO

1. Glob, when used as the operand for an operator expecting a file handle.

        open(FH, &#39;&gt;&#39;, $qfn) or die $!;
        print FH &quot;Hello, World!\n&quot;;

1. String literal, when used as an argument for the a sub parameter with a prototype of `*`.

        sub myprint(*@);
        myprint(FH, &quot;Hello, World\n&quot;);

1. String literal, unless `use strict qw( subs );` is in effect. The documentation defines these are &quot;barewords&quot;, but it also uses that word to refer to other things.

Hopefully, I didn&#39;t miss any.

**CURRENTLY MISSING**:

* `Class` in `Class-&gt;method` and `method Class`.
* `funcname` in `sort funcname`.
* `-foo`
* `${foo}`
* `&lt;&lt;FOO`
* `FOO:`
* `next FOO`
* `__END__`

Thanks to @mosvy, @Grinnz and @stevesliva! Each has uncovered a few cases I had missed.

